{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958010901/0014.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nand continuing\nTHE CHATTAHOOCHEE TRIBUNE\nPublished each Thursday at 15 8. Madison Street\nA JOHN H. PEm NEWSPAPER\nESTABLISHED 1901\nQuincy, Florida\nEntered in th* port ofiie* Quincy, Florida. und*t th* Act *f\nMarch 8 187 S at matter *t th* \u00bboco*d dawu\n\"One Year, $3.00 Two Years, $5.50 Six Months, $1.75\nJ. L. Hutchinson Pubhahar\n\u00a9national fpitptiAL\namnTnwriK\u00dfHl33S\u00df\n\n\"Courage Mounteth with Occasion\"\nMore than three hundred years ago the great Francis\nBacon wrote: \"The virtue of prosperity is temperance; the\nvirtue of adversity is fortitude; which in morals is the more\nX heroical virtue.\"\nA few weeks ago the Vice President of the United States\nheld a press conference, directly following the failure of this\ncountry's first attempt at launching an earth satellite. Mr.\nNixon said: \"Sure we failed. We have before and we will\nagain. But we need to keep our sense of proportion. .We\nhaven't overnight lost our scientific know-how, our ability to\nget things done Let's get away from our weeping walls\nand act like Americans. We've got work to do. Let's get on\nwith it like Americans.\"\nThere is a great gulf of time and language between\nthese two quotations. But both of them stem from the same\nattitude the same outlook on life and the demands of life.\nSome Americans met the Russian scientific successes\nin ostrich-style by trying to ignore them or by depreciat\ning them. Some, at the other extreme, reacted with panic\nand despair an all-is-lost attitude. They showed them\nselves lacking in \"the virtue of adversity\" of which Francis\nBacon wrote. Or they went to the \"weeping walls\" of which\nRichard Nixon spoke.\nBut these people were very much in the minority. The\ngreat majority of Americans fully understand that there is\nwork to do and we must get on with it.\nThe problem, then, is how to do it.\nRussia has been showing the world some of the fruits\nof a harsh materialistic system. Her achievements and\nonly a fool will now try to minimize them have been\nbrought about by force. The abilities of people are carefully,\nefficiently and rigorously channeled into whatever avenues\nbest serve the purposes of the state. The rewards for success\nare often very great; the penalties for failure are often ex\ntremely severe. In any event, the individual has small com\nmand over his own destinies. The state makes the important\ndecisions and provides the directions.\nCan a free people rival and surpass the achievements\nof such a system and still keep their freedom, their tra\nditions, and their national heart and soul?\nHistory tells us that we can. Time and time again the\ni forces of freedom have defeated the forces of tyranny.\nBut the exact opposite also has occurred. Great civili\nzstions have fallen to barbarian hordes. This has happened\nwhen those civilizations grew soft and sleek, contented and\nslack, immersed in luxury and degenerate in character. It\nhas happened when faith was lost in principles and institu\ntions that led to greatness to be replaced by overwhelm\ning cynicism. It has happened, in sum, when fortitude did\nnot come out of adversity, when defeatism prevailed, and\ncitizens turned to the \"weeping walls\".\nWe do not yet know the extent of the efforts that will\nbe needed to build and to maintain the strength necessary\ntor survival. But we do know that they will be great, and\nfuture events may demonstrate that they will be greater than\nanyone realizes now. The burden will fall upon all oil\nIndustry, labor, government. Restraint and wisdom will be\n4 needed by all the national interest must come ahead of\nself-interest. But not one should look on this burden with\ndistaste or fear. The times have brought challenge and\nopportunity and a people which value freedom and honor\nwiH rise voluntarily and in full willingness to meet the chal\nlenge and exploit the opportunity.\nHere another thing that was said many centuries ago is\nperfectly in keeping. Shakespeare put it into the mouth of\none of his characters: \"Courage mounteth with occasion.\"\nThe occasion iq at hand. We must now prove our courage.\nThe Court Under Fire\nThe ground swell of opposition to the maneuverings of\ntiie U. S. Supreme Court is increasing. Evidence of this is\na strong series of editorials by the Indianapolis Star, in\nIndiana, which are being circulated around the country.\nThe cardinal principle and foundation belief of the In*\ndianapolis Star (and many other editors and jurists) is that:\n1. The Supreme Court does not have power to make\nthe \"supreme law of the land.\" Moreover, it does\nnot believe that the Supreme law is whatever the\nCourt says it is.\nIn many recent decisions, the highest Court has\nchanged both the U. S. Constitution and the law of\nthe land without authority.\nCongress, under the power invested in it by the\nConstitution, has the power to limit, restrict and\nchange the authority of the Supreme Court in order\nto require it to conform to the Constitution and to\nlaw. It should do so.\nThese are the sentiments ably expressed in the edi\ntorials of the Indianapolis Star, and which are now being\ncirculated to members of Congress, editors, and to the Su\npreme Court justices themselves by publisher Eugene C.\nPulliam.\nA number of Americans believe that, on the basis of\nnumerous decisions in recent years, the Supreme Court has\nactually become a \"run-away court\". Most of its members\nare not jurists, or have had little judicial experience, and\ntherefore the departure of the present U. S. Supreme Court\nfrom the path of its predecessors becomes disturbing and\neven alarming, and contrary to the best interests of the\nUnited States.\nAccording to the State Board of Conservation, the mullet\nis the Florida saltwater fish caught in greatest numbers. Now\nbeing canned, it compares favorably with salmon in flavor\nand quality.\nThe State Board of Conservation, Tallahassee, has free\nrecipe booklets for preparing Florida seafood, including\ncoquina soup, baked eels, and scallop kabobs.\nFlorida oysters grow nearly twice as fast as oysters\nfrom northern states, reports the State Board of Conservation.\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, JANUARY 9, 1958\nTHE \u201cSOVEREIGN\u201d STATES?\n\u25a0EtltL\nwW'\nMr v J\ni 1\nw/m A\nPeople, Spots In The News\nPUMPKIN\u2019S a mere peanut toH\nYuba, touring circus hippo that\u00df\nstopped in a West Berlin zoo B\nfor a shower and a snack. J\nML\nJj J\nESH \u25a0POOL^TYPE train-\ning reactor designed\nW b y Nuclear Products-Erco divi\nsion of ACF Industries for use in\nIlli engineering schools is studied, in\nW t-W model form, by girl student and\n'Sh yE BE\nMr\nCOMEBACK. Shirley\nTemple, one of greatest F\nchild actresses, back be- |v'\nfore cameras as TV series I\nMH\nhMhmk^^ J\nxwx a- Jt iibbL j^h\nVHHHHhVw llEv m\nNIBBLING thermometers, before traditional ice cream orgy\nof tonsillectomy patients are \"all five\u201d children, ranging\nfrom 9 to 3, of the James Durhams of Lincoln Park, Mich.\nSCOTT'S SCRAP BOOK By R. J SCOTT\nand Ais win\n<AKYLLW MORt<KAH *9l\n4jMO MILU IMMOMt- 'WT A J/\nBuu.-ntefoacycix-fMAiJ.LR.. y//\nPATTEA. M 4M\nsucc^iax.\nPA\nof ra*iMz w\nvoluble. 1/ Zu/A*\nhaaahcul\n^Amlaicah PIKAM/\n-fR^LW WLA^aF- AKPMUSUkLoYKtCALOXIU.FWWf\nar 'flu. AMUWhen OUM FOOD MUi< SuMPLf.\nC*MLMiA>tf. LXPLRIMLMfS Hi BUIL< A ifALoRIMMiK\nPATTER. ROSI aKKMRRy ,K Wu: l A MKH uvw w\nhl> ifRAWURMY. SoML<MU MLRLLY \u00a3A<lMa AMD SUVIMfo\nsuccess io h SoKL-fIMU PtDAUMQ A BICYCLE. M.\ny f L Hard MUSCULAV.WoaK.\nC IW7. Fteftma SjoAnte. h*. W*\u00bbW M*nW.\nLAFF. DAY\n^6 *vf I L Y |xeiHTtfY\nA3 0\nmr, Kh\u00ab teMM Spteiote. tec, V\u00abU n*t\u00ab mnm<\n*Tve taken all the criticism Tm going to take from\nMr. Hartley. How do you spell \u2018resignation?\u2019\nE. H. S. REPORTS\nFROM WASHINGTON\nThe Recession of 1958\nThe Next Six Months\nThe Needed 13 Billions\nDefense to Cost More\nWashington The recession\nwhich is now underway and\nwhich has been felt by some\nsegments of the economy al\nready will continue its course\nuntil the summer. It may reach\nfull swing between April and\nJune, but increased government\nexpenditures might help take up\nthe slack by the time Congress\nadjourns which is estimated\nnow as August.\nThe Internal Revenue Service\nwill feel the recession heavily in\nApril, and also in the current\nmonth, as tax payments are\nmade. The unemployed do not\npay taxes and the number of\nunemployed may reach five mil\nlion by March.\nMoreover, business profits have\nnot been what some expected\nand this will cut down on gov\nernment revenue. As the reces\nsion continues more and more\nbusiness men will cut inven\ntories, as they always do in a\nrecessionary period.\nThis tends to aggrevate the\nsituation, although it makes for\na brisk spur when things begin\nto pick up again.\nOne of the keys to the unfold\ning picture is the farm program,\nand how the farmer fares in\n1958. A good year, perhaps a\nmore effective farm program,\nmight do much to pick business\nup in the fall, although the farm\ner\u2019s buying power today is only\na little over ten per cent of the\nnational total.\nThe downward turn of the\nstock market is looked upon by\nsome as a healthy long-term de\nvelopment. Certainly the prices\nof common stocks are dropping\nto the point where a big break\n\u2014a crash is highly unlikely.\nFor those who have seen prices\nof their stocks dip this should\nbe encouraging news.\nThe view of many economists\nis that the recession was be\nginning unnoticed when\nstocks began to skid in the last\nmonths of 1957. Christmas busi\nness and the last quarter of the\nyear always show comparative\nstrength and 1957 was no ex\nception. The test will come in\nthe first and second quarters of\nthis year.\nThe secret \"Gaither\u201d report,\nwhich was reported on in this\ncolumn four weeks ago, recent\nly was the subject of a much\npublicized copyrighted article in\n\u201cThe Washington Post.\u201d\nWhat that article contained\nwas reported in substance in\nthis column a month ago even\nthough the wire services played\nthat story as a first-run scoop.\nThe article did mention figures\nwhen it discussed recommenda\ntions of the committee which\nlooked into our chances in case\nof a war with Russia.\nThe committee, as reported in\nthis column, recommended that\nthe United States step up its\nspending on defense tremendous\nly. It also recommended that\nthe government begin a huge\nconstruction program con\nstruction of fall-out shelters for\nthe American people.\nThis program alone would\ncost up to five billions of dol\nlars annually. And the commit\ntee thinks that more than this\nshould be added to our aiready\nheavy defense spending, which\napproached 40 billion dollars in\nthe current fiscal year.\nCongress seems certain to in\ncrease defense spending consid\nerably at the coming session, but\nwhether it will hike the figure\nto more than fifty billions as\nhas been recommended is ex\ntremely doubtful.\nIt is known that the President\nis planning to ask Congress to\nstop certain programs and ex\npenditures which are non-essen\ntial and some salons may howl\nabout this when the time comes,\nbut no funds are to be included\nin the budget for these postpon\ned programs.\nAUDIO TV SET\nDallas, Texas Sara Suwal,\nblind for twenty years, has the\nsmallest television set in town.\nFor obvious reasons, it has no\npicture tube. Yet Miss Suwal\nuses it instead of a radio.\nThe set is actually a small cab\ninet about the size of a table\nmodel radio, but its dial has\nnumbers for TV channels. Plug\nged in, it picks up the audio por\ntion of television programs.\nThe set is built by the Ameri\ncan Foundation for the blind.\nMiss Suwal is employed by the\nTexas Commission for the Buna.\nLONESOME COUNTY\nLake City, Col., When it\ncomes to making claims as the\nscantiest populated county in the\nnation, Hinsdale county is m\nthere pitching. Mrs. Jean Vick\ners, county clerk, says the south\ncentral Colorado mountain coun\nty has no more than 150 resi\ndents.\nelectrical\nSERVICE\nAnything from wir\ninqj ex houss to replac\ning a light bulb\nIke Shepard\nat\nBHLL4SHELFER\nFURNITURE CO.\nMAin 7-6543\nRm. MAin \u2019-3071\nStephen Foster\nCarillon Tower\nOpens Sunday\nWhite Springs The 200-foot\nStephens Foster carillon tower,\nnewest addition to the facilities\nat the Stephen Foster Memorial\non the banks of the Suwannee\nRiver here, will be opened to\nthe public for the first time on\nSunday, Jan. 12, and will be site\nof several special events in con\nnection with Stephen Foster\nWeek Jan. 13-19.\nJ. A. Cawthon, Orlando, new\nly-elected chairman of the Ste\nphen Foster Memorial Commis\nsion, announced here today that\nwork on the colonial brick tow\ner, overlooking the 243-acre Fos\nter Memorial park, has been\ncompleted with the exception of\ninstallation of the world\u2019s larg\nest of tubular carillon bells. Ded\nication of the tower is planned\nwhen the bells are completed and\ninstalled several months from\nnow. An electronic carillon al\nready is in use and plays daily\nconcerts of Foster music.\nClimax of Stephens Foster\nweek, honoring the composer of\nFlorida\u2019s state song, \u201cWay Down\nUpon the Suwannee River,\u201d will\nbe the seventh annual contest to\nselect \u201cJeanie With the Light\nBrown Hair.\u201d The Jeanie audi\ntions in the tower auditorium\nJan. 18 will bring together the\nstate\u2019s outstanding girl vocalists\nfrom 17-21 years of age, with the\nwinner being acclaimed as 1958\nJeanie. She and other finalists\nwill be awarded scholarships to\nfurther their musical education.\nContestants are sponsored by\nFlorida Federation of Music\nClubs throughout the state.\nAt their December meeting,\nheld here, members of the Fos\nter Memorial Commission, a state\nagency, elected officers and\nmade plans for observance of\nStephen Foster week. Elected to\nserve with Chairman Cawthon\nwere Mrs. H. G. Miller, Jackson\nville, treasurer, and Mrs. Lillian\nSaunders, White Springs, reelect\ned secretary. Other members of\nthe Commission, who serve with\nout pay and only for the honor\nof service to the State of Flor\nida, are Mrs. Lamar Bledsoe,\nTallahassee, and Beverly Griz\nzard, Fruitland Park, who re\ncently was appointed by the gov\nernor to succeed Earl W. Brown,\nDeLand.\nResolutions honoring Brown\nand the late Cary A. Hardee,\nLive Oak, for their work in be\nhalf of the Foster Memorial\nwere unanimously adopted by\nthe Commission. Brown was an\noriginal appointee to the Com\nmission when it was formed in\n1939 and served for 19 years as\nits chairman, during which time\nthe Memorial was developed in\nto the state\u2019s most-visited, non\ncommercial attraction. Former\nGovernor Hardee was a leader in\nformation of the Stephen Foster\nMemorial Association, a citizens\u2019\ngroup which raised funds to sup\nplement state money in building\nthe half-million dollar carillon\ntower.\nIHE ECONOMY CAR\nOF THE 10W-PRICE THREE\ns*^\nCustom MJ J\nTudor Sedan\nTHE BIG 58 FORD CUSTOM 300\nHere\u2019s the best news of the year for people If you,go for V-8 performance, you can\nwho want to make their car dollars go have your Custom 300 powered by Ford\u2019s\nfurther: all-new Interceptor V-8 with Precision\nWhfle prices of other cars have gone Fuel Induction.\nup for 1958, Ford has reduced the Or if a \"six\u201d suits your driving style\nprices for its popular Custon* 300 better, you can have Ford\u2019s famous\nmodels... below 1957 prices! Mileage Maker Six.\nAnd these new 58 Fords that you can See and Action Test a new Ford Custom\nbuy for less than 1957 prices are beautifully 300 and you\u2019ll aay what they are all saying:\nstyled, handsomely trimmed cars that can For smoother riding comfort, topnotch\nstand up with pride alongside even the performance, tight-fisted economy,- top\ncostliest cars. Yet they are the lowest dollar value you can\u2019t beat the Ford\npriced ears* of the low-price three! for \u20195B. See your Ford Dealer!\n*Battd M MNMHaM nMm\u00ab/aef\u00abrer\u00bb' rtM Mittrtd friMt\nInman-Johnson Motor Company, Inc.\n234 W. Jefferson St. Quincy, Fla*\nH You're Interested in an Used Car Be Sure to See Your Ford Dealer\nIncome Tax\nService To Be\nFurnished By VA\nAn income tax service for\nsome 2,500 Florida veterans and\nothers whose \u201cdirect\u201d home\nloans are held by Veterans Ad\nministration will be provided by\nthe VA regional office in St.\nPetersburg, Florida.\nV. S. Parker, manager, said\nthe office will mail each such\nborrower a statement oi his ac\ncount, including interest and\ntaxes paid during a calendar\nyear 1957, which he may use for\nincome tax purposes if he wishes\nto itemize his deductions.\nThe statement will be mailed\nnot later than January 31, 1958,\nhe said.\nParker emphasized the state\nments will be sent only to those\nveterans whose mortgages are\nheld by the agency under the\ndirect GI loan program, and\nborrowers who have purchased j\nproperties acquired by the VA.\nHe said the service will NOT i\ninclude those whose VA-guaran\nteed mortgages are held by pri\nvate lenders or individuals. The\nlatter must obtain whatever;\ni/t rittr\nJul\nZogHj4 J\nBEBMnEfIEBHBBHHfIfIEE3wBIBEEIENMRfIISHS9Hki&:^:\u25a0?\nNEW LUXURY HEATING\nSAVES US MONEY!\n\"It was hard for us to believe when our dealer\ntold us\u2014but now we\u2019re seeing it with our own eyes!\nWe installed WESIX Automatic Electric Baseboard\nPanels\u2014and found the cost far less than any com\nparable system. And now that we\u2019ve used our sys\ntem through the winter, we find we\u2019re also saving\nmoney on operating costs!\u201d\nWESIX Baseboard Panels provide the finest\nperimeter heating available at any price\u2014y^t their\nease of installation and amazing versatility mean\nsavings for you! Whether your home is under con\nstruction, or an existing home\n\u2014whether you want heat in\none room or the entire house, _\nWESIX Baseboard Panels can WESIX\nbe economically installed to I\nprovide you with clean, com- HIMIMMMMMH\nfortable plus circulating heat\nthe modern way, the electric\nway.\nTaiquin Electric Co-Operative Inc.\nPhone MAin 7-2511 Quincy, Florida\nstatements they need from the\nlenders or those currently hold-\nL g the mortgages.\nFlorida plants and homes\nshould be getting natural gas\nnext fall, says the Houston\nTexas Gas and Oil Corp. The\ncompany is running a pipeline\nfrom Baton Rouge, La. to all\nmajor cities in the Sunshine\nState.\nREADY MIX\nCONCRETE\n\nCONCRETE\nBLOCK\nOakland Concrete\nProducts Company\nAllen Bostick and\nJohn Thomson\nPhone MAin 7-6080","height":"29193","width":"20415"}}
